☕ Java
JRE (Java Runtime Environment) → runs Java bytecode (.class / .jar).

JDK (Java Development Kit) → JRE + compilers + build tools.

Build workflow:

Use Maven/Gradle → produces target/ folder with .jar.

.jar = compiled bytecode + bundled dependencies.

Docker pattern:

Build stage: needs JDK + Maven.

Runtime stage: only JRE (lighter).

dockerfile
FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-17 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN mvn package -DskipTests

FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jre
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app/target/app.jar .
CMD ["java", "-jar", "app.jar"]
🟢 Node.js
Dependencies: installed via npm install → creates node_modules/.

Platform independence: Node.js bytecode runs on any OS with Node runtime.

Docker pattern:

Build stage: install dependencies.

Runtime stage: copy node_modules + source code.

dockerfile
FROM node:20 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json .
RUN npm install
COPY . .

FROM node:20-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app .
CMD ["node", "server.js"]
🐍 Python
Dependencies: installed via pip → stored in Python site‑packages directory.

Platform dependence: compiled C extensions differ per OS.

Docker pattern:

Build stage: needs compilers (build-base, linux-headers, pcre-dev) for native modules.

Runtime stage: only lightweight runtime libs (pcre).

dockerfile
FROM python:3.11-alpine AS builder
WORKDIR /app
RUN apk add --no-cache build-base linux-headers pcre-dev
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --prefix=/install -r requirements.txt

FROM python:3.11-alpine
WORKDIR /app
RUN apk add --no-cache pcre
COPY --from=builder /install /usr/local
COPY . .
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
🔑 General Docker image principles
Separate build vs runtime → multi-stage builds keep images small.

Install dependencies in a different path → copy only what’s needed into runtime.

Build stage → heavy packages (compilers, headers).

Runtime stage → minimal packages (just runtime libs).

Language differences:

Java → .jar file is portable.

Node.js → node_modules copied.

Python → site‑packages compiled per OS.